subSubSection.paragraph:
Diagnosis.
MALE. Clypeus basally elevated, medial depression on anterior margin laterally defined by carinae (
Fig. 5D
); F1 strongly compressed, wider than F2. Pronotum with narrow lateral spot of pale setae (
Fig. 1D
); propodeum dorsally with sparse pale setae (
Fig. 1D
). Metacoxa flattened with dense erect pale microsetae on inner third (
Fig. 7D
). Cuspis stick-like. FEMALE. Frons, vertex, and gena punctures dense to confluent. Mesosoma uniformly yellowish red (
Fig. 2G
); dorsum with coarse confluent punctures (
Fig. 2C
); posterolateral propodeal margin distinctly dentate. T2 pale setal spots small, distance between them 1.0 × or more than spot diameter (
Fig. 2C
); T3–4 with a pair of small lateral pale setal spots, distance between spots and that between spot and lateral margin of tergum approximately equal to spot diameter (
Fig. 2C
); pygidial plate irregularly rugose on anterior 1/3 and smooth posteriorly (
Fig. 12C
).

Forewings fuscous, submarginal cell 1 large, subtriangular, approximately equal in length to marginal cell; 
submarginal cell 2
receiving recurrent vein at midpoint; submarginal cell 3 less distinct than submarginal cell 2 and receiving recurrent vein at midpoint.

